## Objective

Register the CSS `@keyframes drain` animation and Tailwind v4 `@utility animate-drain` so the progress bar can drain via pure CSS animation.

## Implementation

**File:** `apps/client/src/index.css`

Add the keyframe and utility after the existing `@keyframes shimmer-pulse` block (around line 422). The existing pattern in this file is to define keyframes as standalone blocks — follow that convention.

```css
@keyframes drain {
  from {
    width: 100%;
  }
  to {
    width: 0%;
  }
}

@utility animate-drain {
  animation-name: drain;
}
```

Notes:
- The `@utility` directive is Tailwind v4's mechanism for registering custom utilities. This project does not currently use `@utility` anywhere, so this will be the first. The pattern is documented in Tailwind v4's docs.
- The `motion-safe:` prefix (used in the component as `motion-safe:animate-drain`) is a built-in Tailwind variant that maps to `@media (prefers-reduced-motion: no-preference)`. No additional configuration needed.
- The animation duration, timing function, and fill mode are set inline on the element via `style={}` in the component, not in CSS. The keyframe just defines the width transition.

## Verification

- Start the dev server (`pnpm dev`) and inspect that `animate-drain` resolves to the keyframe in browser DevTools
- Verify `motion-safe:animate-drain` applies only when `prefers-reduced-motion` is not `reduce`
- Run `pnpm build` to confirm no CSS compilation errors

